270
00:44:14,088 --> 00:44:17,466
I understand how you feel.
It's hard to be patient.

271
00:44:17,675 --> 00:44:19,635
No one understands how I feel.

272
00:44:20,386 --> 00:44:22,513
I'm supposed to have all this power. . .

273
00:44:22,722 --> 00:44:25,391
. . .and I can't even help
my oldest friend.

274
00:44:26,225 --> 00:44:30,438
You and I know, more than any man alive,
Walter Sullivan put me here.

275
00:44:31,939 --> 00:44:33,608
Now when he needs me most. . . .

276
00:44:34,650 --> 00:44:36,861
Well, he must feel abandoned.

277
00:44:42,867 --> 00:44:44,493
I'll have a press conference.

278
00:44:44,827 --> 00:44:48,581
I'll have Walter come and
I'll embrace him in front of the world.

279
00:44:50,499 --> 00:44:52,168
He'll treasure that.

280
00:44:54,921 --> 00:44:56,672
What a generous gesture.

281
00:44:57,381 --> 00:44:59,675
Thank you, sir. Thank you.

282
00:45:07,767 --> 00:45:09,268
Tennis elbow.

283
00:45:17,944 --> 00:45:20,029
This is getting worse, Gloria.

284
00:45:20,279 --> 00:45:21,948
I need to see a doctor.

285
00:45:22,156 --> 00:45:25,243
The country would have
to be informed, Mr. President.

286
00:45:25,952 --> 00:45:28,162
What happened to my rights to privacy?

287
00:45:28,996 --> 00:45:31,082
I think she nicked a tendon.

288
00:45:31,999 --> 00:45:34,043
Burton says it's a flesh wound.

289
00:45:36,087 --> 00:45:38,714
Since when did you
become an expert, Bill?

290
00:45:39,090 --> 00:45:40,424
You ever been wounded?

291
00:45:40,925 --> 00:45:42,343
Yes, sir. A few times.

292
00:45:48,015 --> 00:45:50,393
You're serious about
this press conference?

293
00:45:50,768 --> 00:45:52,144
Of course I am.

294
00:45:52,645 --> 00:45:54,522
Walter's like a father to me.

295
00:45:55,731 --> 00:45:57,650
Shall I bring Mrs. Richmond home?

296
00:45:58,818 --> 00:46:01,153
I don't think
Mrs. Richmond's mission. . .

297
00:46:01,404 --> 00:46:04,156
. . .to help the poor in Asia
needs to be interrupted.

298
00:46:05,867 --> 00:46:07,410
What do we know so far?

299
00:46:09,287 --> 00:46:11,122
We've checked his license plates.

300
00:46:11,372 --> 00:46:14,083
He stole the car from
a police impoundment lot.

301
00:46:15,793 --> 00:46:18,212
We're not dealing
with a fool, are we?

302
00:46:18,880 --> 00:46:20,298
Has he initiated contact?

303
00:46:21,215 --> 00:46:23,217
Burton doesn't think he will.

304
00:46:25,177 --> 00:46:26,554
I agree.

305
00:46:27,597 --> 00:46:29,640
I apologize for my behavior.

306
00:46:30,141 --> 00:46:32,393
Consider it a blip on the screen.

307
00:46:32,643 --> 00:46:34,937
As far as I'm concerned,
that's all he is.

308
00:46:35,980 --> 00:46:38,482
He could be a little more
than that, Alan.

309
00:46:38,691 --> 00:46:40,026
He saw.

310
00:46:40,234 --> 00:46:44,363
He saw nothing. He saw a drunk woman
who liked rough sex too much.

311
00:46:45,072 --> 00:46:47,408
He's a burglar.
Who's gonna believe him?

312
00:46:47,658 --> 00:46:50,745
After all, it's not as if
he has any evidence.

313
00:47:20,066 --> 00:47:22,235
He's a burglar.
Who 's gonna believe him?

314
00:47:22,485 --> 00:47:25,571
After all, it's not as if
he has any evidence.

315
00:48:32,597 --> 00:48:35,683
Boy, you always did
disappear good, Luther.

316
00:48:36,559 --> 00:48:39,187
You're trying to say
I have a weak face?

317
00:48:39,437 --> 00:48:41,272
No, I'm saying you're lucky.

318
00:48:41,522 --> 00:48:44,859
Some customers, no matter
what I do, still stand out.

319
00:48:45,109 --> 00:48:47,111
How many passports you want?

320
00:48:47,778 --> 00:48:49,447
Four ought to do the trick.

321
00:48:49,655 --> 00:48:53,409
You want different looks, matching
international driver's licenses.

322
00:48:53,659 --> 00:48:55,536
I'll throw in dummy credit cards.

323
00:48:56,370 --> 00:48:58,581
How are the rugs I made you
holding up?

324
00:48:58,873 --> 00:49:01,584
Good. The mustaches
and the beards also.

325
00:49:02,168 --> 00:49:04,503
We try to give quality
for our money.

326
00:49:05,546 --> 00:49:07,757
You leaving the country for permanent?

327
00:49:08,799 --> 00:49:09,884
That could be.

328
00:49:11,552 --> 00:49:15,681
Does it matter where you've been?
I hate doing Asian passport stamps.

329
00:49:15,890 --> 00:49:17,266
No. Make it European.

330
00:49:17,516 --> 00:49:21,687
Caribbean in the wintertime.
How long is all this gonna take?

331
00:49:22,813 --> 00:49:25,650
It usually takes time.
For you, I'll rush it.

332
00:49:27,401 --> 00:49:29,320
You're always dependable, Valerie.

333
00:49:30,112 --> 00:49:31,739
Listen, Luther. . .

334
00:49:32,198 --> 00:49:34,242
. . .I don't wanna know
what you're into.

335
00:49:34,450 --> 00:49:38,538
I do, but I'm not gonna ask you.
But leaving the country forever. . . .

336
00:49:39,330 --> 00:49:40,331
What is it?

337
00:49:40,957 --> 00:49:43,125
I never figured you for a runner.

338
00:49:43,376 --> 00:49:46,963
Thirty percent of my runners
kill themselves within five years.

339
00:49:50,132 --> 00:49:52,885
Right now, five years
doesn't sound too bad.

340
00:49:54,595 --> 00:49:55,763
Take care.

341
00:49:57,431 --> 00:49:58,641
See you.

342
00:49:59,600 --> 00:50:01,978
Okay, see if this makes any sense.

343
00:50:02,270 --> 00:50:04,272
I am Christy Sullivan.

344
00:50:04,856 --> 00:50:07,233
I come in and I surprise a burglar.

345
00:50:08,442 --> 00:50:12,196
Okay, now you're the surprised burglar
coming from the vault.

346
00:50:12,446 --> 00:50:14,532
Gold star. I draw my gun. Boom.

347
00:50:14,782 --> 00:50:17,577
Then why strangle her
when you could just shoot her?

348
00:50:17,785 --> 00:50:21,205
Why do I bother to strip her
and put her clothes back on?

349
00:50:21,455 --> 00:50:23,082
There, I can help you out.

350
00:50:23,332 --> 00:50:26,919
You used to be a dry cleaner
and you love beautiful clothes.

351
00:50:27,169 --> 00:50:29,672
Thanks a lot.
And you dress her because. . . .

352
00:50:29,881 --> 00:50:34,302
She was a good customer and you didn't
want her embarrassed when police came.

353
00:50:35,219 --> 00:50:38,723
She had a 0.21 blood-alcohol level.
Not that it matters.

354
00:50:38,973 --> 00:50:40,516
She didn't drive.

355
00:50:40,725 --> 00:50:44,103
The chauffeurs, they keep
exact mileage on these cars.

356
00:50:44,312 --> 00:50:46,314
They haven't been driven
since they went to Barbados.

357
00:50:46,564 --> 00:50:49,442
I checked every cab
and limo service in the area.

358
00:50:49,692 --> 00:50:52,987
Somebody drove her home. Who?

359
00:50:53,237 --> 00:50:54,947
Why haven't they come forward?

360
00:50:55,156 --> 00:50:57,825
Maybe because whoever drove her
home killed her.

361
00:51:00,453 --> 00:51:01,287
Maybe.

362
00:51:01,996 --> 00:51:03,664
I love this case.

363
00:51:03,873 --> 00:51:04,999
Lieutenant?

364
00:51:05,208 --> 00:51:08,085
Sorry to bother you,
but the phone problems?

365
00:51:08,294 --> 00:51:10,004
-I took care of them.
-Thanks.

366
00:51:11,005 --> 00:51:12,673
Just part of the job.

367
00:51:13,257 --> 00:51:17,261
I hate people who say that.
It is your fucking job.

368
00:51:17,678 --> 00:51:19,847
Remember the bullet hole
in the wall?

369
00:51:20,139 --> 00:51:21,057
Guess what?

370
00:51:21,307 --> 00:51:22,475
No slug.

371
00:51:22,725 --> 00:51:26,562
Why take a slug out of the wall
when there's one stuck in her head?

372
00:51:26,812 --> 00:51:28,731
Different from the one in her body?

373
00:51:29,315 --> 00:51:32,485
Two different guns means two burglars.

374
00:51:32,693 --> 00:51:33,736
Two guys broke in?

375
00:51:33,945 --> 00:51:36,197
They both went out the window?
Bullshit.

376
00:51:37,240 --> 00:51:38,074
By the way. . .

377
00:51:38,533 --> 00:51:41,285
. . .why did he or they
go out the window anyway. . .

378
00:51:41,494 --> 00:51:46,499
. . .when he or they got in by breaking
a zillion dollar security system?

379
00:51:47,124 --> 00:51:49,835
Bill Burton from Secret Service
in the parking lot.

380
00:51:50,086 --> 00:51:53,965
Thanks, Bob.
What's he doing in the parking lot?

381
00:52:02,473 --> 00:52:03,683
Bill Burton. Hi.

382
00:52:03,933 --> 00:52:06,686
Hi. Seth Frank.
To what do I owe the honor?

383
00:52:06,894 --> 00:52:08,396
You must be going crazy. . .

384
00:52:08,604 --> 00:52:11,524
. . .but the boss is interested
about your progress.

385
00:52:11,774 --> 00:52:13,568
Maybe we could help each other.

386
00:52:13,776 --> 00:52:15,444
What do you have in mind?

387
00:52:16,028 --> 00:52:19,615
Well, you know how close
he and Sullivan are, right?

388
00:52:21,576 --> 00:52:23,786
The minute anything breaks. . .

389
00:52:24,579 --> 00:52:26,247
. . .I'll tell the President.

390
00:52:26,455 --> 00:52:28,833
He'd be the first
to alert Mr. Sullivan.

391
00:52:29,083 --> 00:52:30,459
It'd mean a lot to him.

392
00:52:31,168 --> 00:52:33,796
Any red tape you want cut, done.

393
00:52:35,047 --> 00:52:36,716
Here's my numbers.

394
00:52:37,842 --> 00:52:38,676
Any leads?

395
00:52:39,510 --> 00:52:41,679
We're still figuring out
what happened.

396
00:52:41,888 --> 00:52:44,974
-I love playing Sherlock Holmes.
-You guys do that?

397
00:52:45,433 --> 00:52:47,977
I was a state trooper
before the government got me.

398
00:52:48,394 --> 00:52:50,188
Wait. You're that Bill Burton?

399
00:52:50,521 --> 00:52:54,483
-I was younger and dumber then.
-I was younger. I'm dumber now.

400
00:52:54,734 --> 00:52:56,319
Keep in touch.

401
00:53:22,637 --> 00:53:25,556
My chef makes them especially for me.

402
00:53:25,765 --> 00:53:28,434
I promise you, they're sinful.

403
00:53:29,435 --> 00:53:31,562
You're a salesman, Mr. Sullivan.

404
00:53:32,897 --> 00:53:35,316
This is a new arena for me.

405
00:53:35,942 --> 00:53:39,570
But from what I'm told,
you have a flawless reputation.

406
00:53:40,279 --> 00:53:43,074
Which is why I need to employ you,
Mr. McCarty.

407
00:53:43,324 --> 00:53:44,200
Understood.

408
00:53:44,700 --> 00:53:47,453
I don't know who it is I'm after yet.

409
00:53:47,662 --> 00:53:49,205
Until I do. . .

410
00:53:49,455 --> 00:53:51,916
. . .you wait in Washington
for instructions.

411
00:53:54,544 --> 00:53:56,379
That's out of the question.

412
00:53:57,713 --> 00:53:59,340
Mine is not creative work.

413
00:53:59,590 --> 00:54:02,218
I do it because I enjoy
living beyond my means.

414
00:54:02,468 --> 00:54:04,470
I can't afford to sit around.

415
00:54:06,681 --> 00:54:09,767
My father died
when I was 1 0 years old.

416
00:54:09,976 --> 00:54:13,145
He was a miner.
He died of lung disease.

417
00:54:14,146 --> 00:54:16,482
I became rich at 25.

418
00:54:16,691 --> 00:54:20,152
The first thing I did was buy
that mine, close it down. . .

419
00:54:20,361 --> 00:54:24,532
. . .and give every miner
$50,000 to retire on.

420
00:54:27,451 --> 00:54:30,413
You will wait in Washington,
Mr. McCarty.

421
00:54:30,621 --> 00:54:34,959
And I will put
one million dollars' expenses. . .

422
00:54:35,167 --> 00:54:37,211
. . .in a Swiss bank of your choosing.

423
00:54:37,545 --> 00:54:39,839
And when the time comes. . .

424
00:54:40,464 --> 00:54:42,508
. . .2 million dollars a bullet.

425
00:54:45,136 --> 00:54:46,762
You are a salesman, sir.

426
00:54:49,640 --> 00:54:51,684
Selling sin is easy.

427
00:54:58,649 --> 00:55:00,860
-Who is he?
-It's Luther Whitney. . .

428
00:55:01,110 --> 00:55:03,571
. . .one of the great thieves
of the world.

429
00:55:04,363 --> 00:55:06,782
I've been going nuts.
I was up all night.

430
00:55:08,576 --> 00:55:11,537
I remembered your notion
how it was two burglars.

431
00:55:11,787 --> 00:55:15,249
Around dawn, I thought,
"What if it's not two burglars. . .

432
00:55:15,458 --> 00:55:18,628
. . .but just one guy trying
to make it look like two?"

433
00:55:19,629 --> 00:55:22,548
I called my buddy at the Bureau.
They keep track.

434
00:55:22,757 --> 00:55:26,510
There's only half a dozen guys
who could've done the Sullivan job.

435
00:55:26,761 --> 00:55:28,387
I've been tracing all six.

436
00:55:28,638 --> 00:55:30,640
Whitney's the only guy
that lives here.

437
00:55:31,307 --> 00:55:35,394
-Why haven't I ever heard of him?
-He hasn't been arrested in 20 years.

438
00:55:35,645 --> 00:55:38,397
What's this? His graduation
picture from Harvard?

439
00:55:38,606 --> 00:55:41,651
That's history.
He was just a punk, part of a gang.

440
00:55:42,109 --> 00:55:43,402
Three-time loser.

441
00:55:43,653 --> 00:55:45,112
Since he got out last. . .

442
00:55:45,863 --> 00:55:47,156
. . .no one's touched him.

443
00:55:48,658 --> 00:55:52,328
When something big comes up,
they question him, but nothing sticks.

444
00:55:52,537 --> 00:55:53,412
Oh, Seth.

445
00:55:54,163 --> 00:55:56,123
We can make this stick.

446
00:55:57,041 --> 00:55:58,417
I bet you he's our guy.

447
00:55:58,668 --> 00:56:01,379
He's a local.
You can't ask for anything more.

448
00:56:02,463 --> 00:56:04,090
Well, we got a problem.

449
00:56:04,340 --> 00:56:05,508
What?

450
00:56:06,842 --> 00:56:08,719
He hasn't killed anyone in 45 years.

451
00:56:09,971 --> 00:56:10,930
Korea.

452
00:56:11,180 --> 00:56:12,682
So what? He's a veteran.

453
00:56:12,890 --> 00:56:16,143
Not just a veteran,
he's a wounded veteran.

454
00:56:16,394 --> 00:56:18,229
I got his war record here.

455
00:56:18,563 --> 00:56:22,608
Battles, commendations,
decorations up the kazoo.

456
00:56:23,860 --> 00:56:25,611
He lives alone on disability.

457
00:56:25,820 --> 00:56:28,114
That's what he says anyway.

458
00:56:29,115 --> 00:56:32,410
But I don't see him as a killer.
He's just a great thief.

459
00:56:32,660 --> 00:56:35,329
And besides, I don't do war heroes.

460
00:57:21,918 --> 00:57:23,294
Boy, you must be smart.

461
00:57:24,921 --> 00:57:26,088
Pardon me?

462
00:57:27,298 --> 00:57:30,176
It usually takes you guys
a week to get to me.

463
00:57:32,428 --> 00:57:34,055
Oh, Seth Frank.

464
00:57:34,513 --> 00:57:37,475
I recognize your picture
from the newspaper.

465
00:57:37,725 --> 00:57:39,352
Luther Whitney.

466
00:57:40,228 --> 00:57:41,646
Nice to meet you.

467
00:57:42,730 --> 00:57:47,235
Would you like a signed confession now
or do you want coffee first?

468
00:57:47,443 --> 00:57:52,281
Before I send you away for life,
I should probably check out your alibi.

469
00:57:52,532 --> 00:57:56,285
I was watching a football game
with an old friend, Red Bransford.

470
00:57:56,536 --> 00:57:58,746
He owns a saloon here in town.

471
00:57:59,622 --> 00:58:01,499
You can ask me about the game.

472
00:58:01,749 --> 00:58:03,543
I could be lying.

473
00:58:04,669 --> 00:58:06,254
You been following the case?

474
00:58:06,462 --> 00:58:07,672
Yeah, I have.

475
00:58:07,880 --> 00:58:09,799
I love true crime.

476
00:58:10,258 --> 00:58:13,803
FBI says there's only a few guys
who could have handled this job.

477
00:58:14,053 --> 00:58:16,472
I got a list here.
You're on it.

478
00:58:17,056 --> 00:58:18,558
How I wish it were true.

479
00:58:20,935 --> 00:58:24,188
This person,
they go in the front door. . .

480
00:58:24,397 --> 00:58:27,525
. . .and out a window, down a rope
in the middle of the night?

481
00:58:28,359 --> 00:58:31,028
Now, if I could do
something like that. . .

482
00:58:31,237 --> 00:58:33,781
. . .I'd be the star
of my AARP meetings.

483
00:58:34,657 --> 00:58:38,995
-What's that? The American--
-Association of Retired Persons.

484
00:58:41,581 --> 00:58:43,791
Luther, why was this so difficult?

485
00:58:44,625 --> 00:58:47,169
You want me to help you
solve your case?

486
00:58:47,420 --> 00:58:49,046
Just looking for insight.

487
00:58:49,255 --> 00:58:50,673
How would you--?

488
00:58:51,257 --> 00:58:54,051
Scratch that.
How would one go about it?

489
00:58:54,302 --> 00:58:56,721
What kind of person
should I look for?

490
00:58:58,431 --> 00:59:01,559
Except for the rope trick,
an older person, like me.

491
00:59:01,809 --> 00:59:03,394
Because?

492
00:59:04,103 --> 00:59:05,897
Well, you need patience.

493
00:59:06,147 --> 00:59:09,442
The secret is research, research
and research. I've read that.

494
00:59:09,650 --> 00:59:11,444
What kind of research?

495
00:59:13,154 --> 00:59:16,741
Well, from what I saw on the tube,
this is a rather large home.

496
00:59:16,949 --> 00:59:19,368
Must be an architectural office.

497
00:59:19,619 --> 00:59:22,622
You'd go to the library,
go through public records. . .

498
00:59:22,872 --> 00:59:26,334
. . .find out where that architectural
office is and break in.

499
00:59:26,584 --> 00:59:30,087
And then you xerox the plans
and get them back by morning.

500
00:59:30,338 --> 00:59:32,298
Why not just steal them?

501
00:59:32,882 --> 00:59:35,134
Anyone can break into
an office, but doing it. . .

502
00:59:35,384 --> 00:59:38,638
. . .without having people know
you were there is the trick.

503
00:59:38,888 --> 00:59:41,349
Then there's the general contractor.

504
00:59:41,557 --> 00:59:44,060
And then there's the security company.

505
00:59:44,435 --> 00:59:49,232
Do you realize the skill of breaking
the security of a security company?

506
00:59:49,774 --> 00:59:52,193
I don't know how those guys do it.

507
00:59:53,903 --> 00:59:56,364
Why go to all that trouble, Luther?

508
00:59:57,156 --> 01:00:00,952
There's a vault in the house.
There must be a secret way into it.

509
01:00:01,160 --> 01:00:03,204
There was.
That's what I don't get.

510
01:00:04,080 --> 01:00:05,164
How do you mean?

511
01:00:05,414 --> 01:00:08,668
This guy obviously did
the research you're talking about.

512
01:00:08,918 --> 01:00:10,753
So why does he take a crowbar. . .

513
01:00:10,962 --> 01:00:14,215
. . .to open the vault when
there's a clicker right there?

514
01:00:14,465 --> 01:00:15,383
A clicker?

515
01:00:15,591 --> 01:00:18,678
Well, a gizmo, like a VCR remote.

516
01:00:21,264 --> 01:00:23,474
Sounds amazing to me.

517
01:00:24,934 --> 01:00:27,645
Must've been a lot
of valuables in that vault.

518
